[Student "S"]
{Partner's 2NT is the lebensohl convention. He requests that you bid 3\C as a relay, which you do. Partner now bids 3NT.  

Partner's 2NT is the lebensohl convention. He requests that you bid 3\C as a relay, which you do. Partner now bids 3NT. 

When partner bids 3NT AFTER the lebensohl 2NT, he is suggesting you play there, and he guarantees a stopper in their suit. You are happy to pass.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \DQ. East attacks in \Ds and you must make an immediate choice. Hold up, win in dummy, or win in your hand.

Winner List: \S = 2 : \H = 1 : \D = 2 : \C = 0 :: Total = 5

First decide about what to do at trick #1. If you hold up and East plays another \D, no harm will be done. But probably no good will be done either because East is likely to have 6 \Ds, leaving West with just a singleton anyway. But what if East pockets the one \D trick and switches to \Hs, a suit where you only have one stopper? Since that might turn out badly, you should <b>NOT</b> hold up.

As to which hand to win it in, that's easy. You need to preserve any dummy entries that you can so you win the first trick with your \DK. 

Now you establish some \C winners. You play the \CJ and both defenders play low. 

You have to assume that defenders good enough to hold up their \CA at the first opportunity will be good enough to do it on the second play also. But you can thwart them by next playing your \CT and overtaking with dummy's \CQ. Even if they do hold up again you can continue with another \C from dummy to establish the suit while you still have the \DA for an entry.

If you fail to overtake the second \C West will hold up the \CA again.

Then you will lose all those \C tricks in dummy.}
[Play "W"]DQ

