[Student "S"]
{<b><i></i></b>The question is: Do you use Transfers after a 1NT OVERCALL? And in particular, can you bid the opponent's suit and have it mean a transfer instead of a cue-bid? This is something you and your partner need to agree on - as for me and my partner, we think 2\D is a transfer. Partner replies 2\H.  

<b><i></i></b>The question is: Do you use Transfers after a 1NT OVERCALL? And in particular, can you bid the opponent's suit and have it mean a transfer instead of a cue-bid? This is something you and your partner need to agree on - as for me and my partner, we think 2\D is a transfer. Partner replies 2\H. 

With 10 points you are between Invitational and Game-forcing. Which means you bid either 2NT or 3NT, whichever suits your fancy. Today let's say it is 3NT which partner converts to 4\H.

The contract would be 4\H played by West.

East plays 4\H. South leads the \D9. North wins the first trick with the \DA, then plays \DQ. You take your \DK now, fearing that the next one could be ruffed by South.

Loser List: \S = 1 : \H = 1 : \D = 2 : \C = 1 :: Total = 5

You hope North, who opened the bidding, (as South before the hands were rotated), will have the \SK, which would reduce your losers to 4.

You win the second \D and play your \HQ, taken by North with the \HK. He cashes the \DJ, South following, then exits with a small \H. 

Win this trump and play one more, pulling North's last trump and ending in dummy. Play a \S to your \SQ (which wins) then play \SA and ruff a \S in dummy. North follows with the \S7, \SJ and \SK. Now you must try the \C finesse, but through whom? 

Is it a 50-50 guess? Or is North more likely to have the \CQ since he had the opening hand? 

No, it is not a 50-50 guess. No, North doesn't have the \CQ, South does. If you watched the cards that North has played you will realize he started with 3-3-4-3 distribution. You will also know that he started with 14 points outside the \C suit. If he had the \CQ he would have a balanced 16 point hand and would have opened 1NT, not 1\D. So South has the \CQ.

You can go through 100 hands and on 99 of them it won't matter if you pay attention to the cards played by the defenders or not.

But if you don't pay attention on all 100 of them you will miss the one time where your attention was needed.}
[Play "W"]D9

